## How to load the custom cca module
```bash
cd custom_cca

# only do this when you have my_cca previously loaded
# check with 'lsmod | grep my_cca'
sudo rmmod my_cca

sudo insmod my_cca.ko

# Verify it is loaded and recognized by the TCP stack
sysctl net.ipv4.tcp_allowed_congestion_control

# Set the custom algorithm as default
# You can specify which protocol to use in Python as well (Better)
sudo sysctl -w net.ipv4.tcp_congestion_control=my_cca
sudo dmesg -w
```


## Enabling the loading of the custom cca module (secure boot)
- **Note that step1 ~ step3 only needs to be done once.**
- **Note that even if you modify the system to use my_cca, some already established TCP will still be using my_cca. You need to wait until these TCP sessions are done to do** `sudo rmmod my_cca`
1. Create a signing key
```bash
mkdir -p ~/module-signing
cd ~/module-signing

openssl req -new -x509 -newkey rsa:2048 \
  -keyout MOK.priv \
  -outform DER \
  -out MOK.der \
  -nodes -days 36500 \
  -subj "/CN=My Kernel Module Signing Key/"

```

2. Enroll the key
```
sudo mokutil --import MOK.der
```

3. Reboot
- On reboot, the MOK manager screen should appear
- Choose:
  - Enroll MOK
  - Continue
  - Yes
  - enter the password you set (pass: **NAL-123-neut**)

4. Sign your module (**This has to be done everytime you rebuild the module**)
```bash
cd /home/nal/NAL_edwin_sm/client_server/custom_cca

sudo /usr/src/linux-headers-$(uname -r)/scripts/sign-file \
  sha256 \
  ~/module-signing/MOK.priv \
  ~/module-signing/MOK.der \
  my_cca.ko

```
